posts.name: Joseph Walters
posts.cooked:
Perhaps there is an intentionally externally exposed connector as a “Test Point”?

You can see it at 3 locations along the bus. If there was bus misbehavior you could measure the resistance at these test points and help narrow down the problem if there is more or less than the intended 60ohms fully terminated design resistance.

You could use these inspection sites to hook up an o-scope and look at bus health and speed at an electrical signal level.

posts.name: Luca Younes
posts.cooked:
I can confirm that TP = test point. On Roti we just have loose-hanging female headers, but I wish we used panel mount banana plug receptacles (like the ones on multimeters).

We thankfully did not have to use them this season, but I can think of a few times in past years when I had to trim off some insulation to do the tests you mentioned.

In case anyone is curious, this video covers some debugging tests you can do with a multimeter on a CAN bus.

The robot weighs around 120lbs and the shooter is about 18lbs.

We found through testing that the mecanums and tapered rollers were really important for getting consistent shots. When we pick up a note off the ground, the intake will often hand it off to the shooter in a very deformed state. Forcing the note to expand back to its original shape made our shots were much more consistent. So the mecanums don’t center inward like most intakes usually would- instead, they’re trying to do the opposite. The tapered rollers are printed out of PLA and wrapped in cat tongue grip tape. At the widest point, in the center, they have enough compression to move the note, and on the sides, because there is no compression, the note expands back into it’s original shape more easily.

posts.name: Shiloh Robinson
posts.cooked:
dwwright:

How was the backlash in your shooter pivot? Did you implement any tricks to try and reduce mechanical backlash?

Technically, there is backlash in the system, but we do a few things to counteract it. There are 2x50lb gas springs pushing up on the pivot. This more than counteracts the weight of the shooter being pulled down, which biases the backlash to one side and means the “functional backlash” is pretty much zero. Ie. there’s not a point where the motor is turning, but the pivot is not. We also use shim stock to shim all of our gears and have inline chain tensioners. The gas shocks also counteract the movement of the elevator going up when we shoot.

CooperSurma:

Where did you get these pulleys on your elevator? (or were they made in-house)

We bought the pulleys off Mcmaster . They are a bit pricy at $5.17 per pulley, but they work very well and I don’t think we have had any fail on us.

CooperSurma:

What is the purpose of this plate on your superstructure?

This is a camera protector plate. On the actual robot, the ends of the plate are bent outwards a little bit so if we ever get hit, there’s more space for them to momentarily bend in and still not hit the cameras.

CooperSurma:

What was the reasoning behind having the tubing on the first stage of the elevator be 1/8" while having the base stage (“stage 0”) be 1/16"? My intuition says it should be the opposite

After running the robot for a few competitions, these were the tubes that were being dented the most. We also noticed a lot of denting in our first stage tube in last year’s robot when we used 1/16 wall tube. There are also countersunk bolts in that 1st stage, so the tube needs to be thick enough to get those in.

posts.name: Luca Younes
posts.cooked:
Yes, that’s what we do…

Actually, lots of things on our bus are short stubs. I think the official CAN spec is 1 foot or less… We’ve never really had an issue with short “branches”/stubs, and the reliability advantage of being able to have one continuous wire as the main loop is worth it IMO.

I think the goal for CAN on an FRC robot is basically to minimize connectors on any line that takes down the whole bus if broken - Roti’s bus only has the one weidmuller connection to the carnivore on our main bus’s critical path, and it’s been dead reliable.

posts.name: Joseph Walters
posts.cooked:
If it’s not t-taps I bet they solder and as a simplification do not consider this joint a connector.

I personally don’t like t-taps/insulation piercing connections long-term on vibration applications like moving machines as a general rule (RJ-45 even…but it is what it is and in that application has proven reliable enough).

I suppose robots are different than work though with design life in the tens to low hundreds of hours of operation vs thousands of hours of continuous operation.

posts.name: Luca Younes
posts.cooked:
We use IDC (insulation displacement connector) t-taps in some places - absolutely no soldering as it causes stress concentrations, is difficult to inspect, and takes a long time.

We used krakens for our drivetrain, so we were able to strip the middle of the can wire and fold it over into a ring terminal. So yes, one continuous run of copper from carnivore to termination resistor.

Other subsystems (and encoders) branch off using the connectors you linked.

You can read a bit more about our wiring practices here … it’s not all 100% updated right now, but still relevant…
